Introduction¶

Descriptions: Every year for the past 40-plus years, Peter and Rosemary Grant have gone to the Galpagos island of Daphne Major and collected data on Darwin's finches.We will use this data to study how the beak depth (the distance, top to bottom, of a closed beak) of the finch species Geospiza scandens has changed over time. The Grants have noticed some changes of beak geometry depending on the types of seeds available on the island, and they also noticed that there was some interbreeding with another major species on Daphne Major, Geospiza fortis. These effects can lead to changes in the species over time.In this project we are going to look at the beak depth of G. scandens on Daphne Major in 1975 and in 2012.

Finch_beaks dataset columns descriptions:

  • band: Index.
  • species: Finches species (fortis, scandens).
  • Beak_length: Finches beak length.
  • Beak_depth: Finches beak depth.

Questions:¶

1. Has Finches beaks average length been evolved from 1975 to 2012?

2. Has Finches beaks average depth been evolved from 1975 to 2012?

3. Is there any correlation between Finches beaks length and beak length?

4. Is Finches beak length statistically significant in predicting length?

Cleaning Data¶

Quality issues¶

  1. Change columns names to be the same on two datasets.
  2. Add year column to each dataframe.
  3. Merge dataframes into one dataframe df.
  4. Change species column data type into category to save memory.
  5. Drop duplicated values.

AB Testing¶

  • Now I'm going to make A/B test to check:

    • If finches beaks average length has been evolved from 1975 to 2012 or not.
    • If finches beaks average depth has been evolved from 1975 to 2012 or not.

  • Alpha level will be 0.05 so the results will be with 95% confidence.

  • I will use bonferroni correction because I'm going to check the results for 2 metrics length and depth so our real Alpha level is (0.05 / 2 = 0.025)

Problem Statement:¶

1. Has Finches beaks average length been evolved from 1975 to 2012?¶

Null hypothesis is: Fenchies beak length mean is the same in 1975 and 2012 for both species (Fortis and scandens)

alternative hypothesis is: Fenchies beak length mean is not the same in 1975 and 2012 for both species (Fortis and scandens)

2. Has Finches beaks average depth been evolved from 1975 to 2012?¶

Null hypothesis is: Fenchies beak depth mean is the same in 1975 and 2012 for both species (Fortis and scandens)

alternative hypothesis is: Fenchies beak depth mean is not the same in 1975 and 2012 for both species (Fortis and scandens)

\begin{equation} H_{0} : \mu_{2012} - \mu_{1975} = 0 \end{equation}
\begin{equation} H_{1} : \mu_{2012} - \mu_{1975} != 0 \end{equation}

Bootstrap the data by resampling the dataset with replacement for Fortis length and depth.¶

In [46]:
fortis_len_diffs = []
fortis_dep_diffs = []

for i in range (10000):
    fortis_boot_sample = fortis.sample(frac=1, replace=True)
    foris_len_mean_75 = fortis_boot_sample[fortis_boot_sample.year==1975].blength.mean()
    foris_len_mean_2012= fortis_boot_sample[fortis_boot_sample.year==2012].blength.mean()
    fortis_len_diff = foris_len_mean_2012 - foris_len_mean_75
    fortis_len_diffs.append(fortis_len_diff)
    
    foris_dep_mean_75 = fortis_boot_sample[fortis_boot_sample.year==1975].bdepth.mean()
    foris_dep_mean_2012= fortis_boot_sample[fortis_boot_sample.year==2012].bdepth.mean()
    fortis_dep_diff = foris_dep_mean_2012 - foris_dep_mean_75
    fortis_dep_diffs.append(fortis_dep_diff)
    
fortis_len_diffs = np.array(fortis_len_diffs)
fortis_dep_diffs = np.array(fortis_dep_diffs)
In [47]:
# make sampling destribution when null hypothesis is true for fortis length

null_1 = np.random.normal(0,np.std(fortis_len_diffs), 10000)
In [48]:
# drawing sampling distrbution using the observed fortis length diff to check p-value
plt.rcdefaults()
plt.hist(null_1)
plt.axvline(fortis_length_diff, lw=2,color="r");
In [49]:
# calculate P-value for fortis length difference

fortis_len_p_value = (null_1< fortis_length_diff).mean() + ( null_1> (0 + (0 - fortis_length_diff))).mean()
fortis_len_p_value
Out[49]:
0.5723

Result¶

While P-value is larger than Alpha level we fail to reject the null hypothesis for fortis beak length. Based on this data we have a statistical evidence that the Fortis beak length hasn't been evolved from 1975 to 2012 with 95% confidence.

AB test result¶

Based on previous data we have a statistical evidence that:

  1. Fortis beak length hasn't been evolved from 1975 to 2012.
  2. Fortis beak depth has been evolved from 1975 to 2012.
  3. Scandens beak length has been evolved from 1975 to 2012.
  4. Scandens beak depth has been evolved from 1975 to 2012.

Conclusions¶

A. Descriptive statistics conclutions:¶

1. 90% of finches have got taller beak length in 2012.

2. 97% of finches have got shorter beak depth in 2012.

3. The length of Fortis specie beak has got little taller in 2012 and the length of scandens specie beak has got shorter in 2012.

4. The depth of Fortis specie beak has got shorter in 2012 and the depth of scandens specie beak has got taller in 2012.

  • Note: These conclusions applies only on the data that we already have.

B. AB Test conclutions:¶

1. We have a statistical evidence that the Fortis beak length hasn't been evolved from 1975 to 2012 with 95% confidence

2.We have a statistical evidence that the Fortis beak depth has been evolved from 1975 to 2012 with 95% confidence.

3. We have a statistical evidence that the Scandens beak length has been evolved from 1975 to 2012 with 95% confidence.

4. We have a statistical evidence that the The scandens beak depth has been evolved from 1975 to 2012 with 95% confidence.

C. Regression analysis conclutions:¶

1. There is a weak positive correlation between Scandens beak length and depth.

1. There is a strong positive correlation between Fortis fenchies beak length and depth.

3. For every 1 mm increase in Fortis fenchies beak depth we predict that their beak length will increase with 0.6919 mm.

4. For every 1 mm increase in Scandens fenchies beak depth we predict that their beak length will increase with 0.5176 mm.

5. Scandens beak depth is statistically significant in predicting their beak length with 95% confidence

6. Fortis beak depth is statistically significant in predicting their beak length with 95% confidence.

Limitations¶

1. 1975 dataset has more samples than 2012 dataset.

2. Fortis specie samples counts is larger in 1975 and scandens specie samples count is larger in 2012. This difference in samples count will be considered as a bias and it may affect our AB test results accuracy.
